caption: This place is Cold Storage get pretty big and they close at so you will have to get there early. The Cold Storage is the best ever I definitely recommend.

Loved this place so much the first time, that I went with a different group of people the following week! They have an AMAZING happy hour with $1 oysters, $5 draft beers, $7 roses and $10 cocktails!  The oysters aren't your regular dollar oysters. They are big, thick, and juicy!! And I'm not exaggerating, some of them were OVERFLOWING out of the shell. SO good. They have a variety of hot sauces that you can try with your oysters.  We also got other HH specials such as the cod croquettes and this delicious ceviche. The croquettes have a light breading and the filling had both potatoes and bits of fish texture, which made it really tasty. It also came with a nice creamy aioli.  The ceviche tasted FRESH! At first, we thought it was the salsa for the chips but eventually when the seafood started showing up in our scoops, we realized it was the ceviche we ordered!  Can't wait to come again! It's actually pretty easy to get a table around 515-545 so it'd be a good after work spot

This place is ok in my opinion. Probably great for those who like oysters, crab, and lobster. I like those meals, and they are good here, but I feel the rest of their menu is a little too fancy for me or the food is just ok (fish sandwich, Nashville chicken, twice baked potatoes, tuna tartar (with raw egg yolk on tab??), etc.). Happy hour has decent prices and the happy hour wines are good.

One of my favorite places for HH when I’m craving seafood in the Fulton Market neighborhood. Great HH specials like $1 oysters, white fish dip, beer and wine. The complimentary salt and vinegar chips are deliciously addictive! Get there early or the bar seating fills up. Another treat for history buffs is eating in the building itself, which used to be a 1920s 10-story refrigeration facility occupied by Fulton Market Cold Storage Company before they abandoned the building due to gentrification of the former meatpacking district in 2012 and moved to the ‘burbs. Check out Gary Jensen’s time lapse of thawing the former freezer which had unworldly ice crystals to expose the huge support columns and concrete walls you see now. It reportedly took a couple weeks to thaw. Enjoy a cocktail and some oysters in a century-old cold storage. That’s pretty cool.

Service is always excellent. One of the best places for oysters.  One of my local favorites. Update Its good to come out and support our local guys during COVID, so we decided to stop by one of our favorite spots.  I guess this place has been hit harder than what I would have expected.  You could come here, and get a variety of oysters and cocktails, with their own sauces.   They couldn't even find their sauces this time around when we went.  So disappointing . Now it was pretty much limited to 3 regions for oysters, and even for cocktails, they really only had one special.  Granted with the full bar at their disposal, they can make anything, but its nice to be able to try distinct hand crafted cocktails that places like this usually like to push.  Really hope this place recovers and gets back to what they use to do.   If your looking for good oysters and a variety of cocktails, there are other places not hit as hard and have stayed true to their theme.
Good food
american food and the scene here is better than most. It was so fresh. Fast and courteous service. The place has a great atmosphere. Menu is like a cafe in Boston I liked.

This is a review specifically of the Joomak pop-up by chef Eddie Lee in July. This was honestly the best meal I've had this year. Every single dish was phenomenal, though my personal favorite was the beef tartare - the inclusion of pears was very creative. I would recommend getting 2 dishes per person, slightly more if you're hungry.

Don’t miss out on these $1 oysters for Happy Hour! They have the cutest patio outside for COVID and had music playing which I loved. Very friendly staff and everything was very tasty. Giving 4 stars because I thought it was slightly overpriced and the menu they have right now is much smaller than what they had online. I wish they would have updated or posted something saying they had a smaller menu for Covid because there were some picky eaters in our group and I think it would have influenced our decision to visit. But for my tasting, it was perfect! Loved the crab cakes

We had reservations January 31th 8:30pm. We were seated and offer the $48.00 restaurant week menu only. I asked about the $36.00 menu, waiter had to ask the manager, never came back to our table. I went to the hostess who did the offer the $36.00 menu. My spouse had exit the restaurant at this time, when I returned another hostess said she had to wait for the manager. We left the restaurant, had our dinner elsewhere, very disappointed. We will not return.

All of the food was good though and any of the seafood/fish dishes would be delicious. They also have no fish dishes if fish isn't your thing.

The food is definitely expensive but out of this world.  I definitely recommend the nashville hot fried shrimp served on Texas toast with slaw.  I'm not sure how they got shrimp that big but I'm not going to ask questions because it was so good.  I also really enjoyed the crab knuckles but was expecting a lot more meat than was actually served.

Went during oyster happy hour to celebrate a 5 year anniversary. The oysters were all very appealing and fresh (Delaware, VA) and served with a nice cocktail sauce and a mignonette. There was also some nice house hot sauces (the "Fresnos and Enemies" was the favorite of ours) to go with the food. We also got a delicious bowl of split pea and ham hock soup. For mains, we did the fish and chips and the hot fried shrimp. The fish and chips were tried and true, but the shrimp (inspired by Nashville hot chicken) was the star! Highly recommend. Also, our server Nestor was very kind and attentive and even hooked it up with a cute narwhal cookie and some truffles as a thanks and congrats to our five years celebrated. Definitely going back!

Very cool decor centered around the raw bar in the middle. Lots of smaller sharing options as well as larger entrees. Staff is helpful in navigating the menu, which has lots of parts.  Tins are fun, and exactly what they sound like. Imagine a large, upscale can of sardines (or clams, mackerel, etc) served on a plate with butter, lemon, and saltines. I was a big fan.  Also, salmon belly! I had no idea that was a thing, but damn was it good. I'd definitely go again (especially to hit up $1 oyster happy hour).

Great food options are not matched by the service. During the dinner for four:  - Unfinished glass was taken away - Three by dozen oysters served without a single oyster fork - When inquired about the forks we were told "we got them, just not enough" (huh? in an oyster place?!) - Plates are changed all the time, to the point of annoyance, but silverware taken and not replaced at times until asked - Steak tartar and burrata salad took so much time to bring that we finished two dozen oysters - leisurely - Three identical espressos brought after taking an order of 2x double and 1x single  Any of those in isolation would be an excusable nuisance. Altogether it is a pattern of poor management and a botched experience.  The food, again, was awesome - great quality and flavors. As of today Google claims this place is in the $$ price range. Nah, it is clearly $$$ - just look up in the menu what you'd have for a dinner.

Great bar, great food. Simple and familiar concept well executed. The real stand outs were first the female mixologist behind the bar who delivered a perfect Corpse Revived #2 & the best Negroni. The equally great standout was the kitchen. There were many dishes I'd come back for; oysters,  grilled octopus (so easy to get wrong and rubbery but this was perfectly prepared), spicy shisito peppers with anchovies and the giant shrimp (again, more often than not slightly overcooked - these were flawless). Finally the service was impeccable. I've eaten at a few restaurants in this area in this last week and this is one of the best.
Love the seafood and casual atmosphere...looking forward to our next time"

Some hits some misses. The special halibut fish collar was really good. So were shishito and asparagus. Oyster bar was nice. The octo salad was underwhelming as was the coconut ceviche. Dessert was a highlight. Shakes and pies!! Delicious.

This place was truly memorable. The atmosphere harkened back to old fish markets mixed with modern industrial design. The server was very knowledgable regarding the food. Which was glorious! We sampled their raw bar, all of what we had was very good quality and well sourced. The smoked mussels and seared scallops were especially tasteful! Their desert menu was fantastic and all made in house. I will definitely be eating there again!
